"Im E.-S., Coppola E., Giorgi F., Bi X.","Local effects of climate change over the Alpine region: A study with a high resolution regional climate model with a surrogate climate change scenario",2010,"Geophysical Research Letters","37","5", L05704,"","",,,10.1029/2009GL041801,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-77949310699&partnerID=40&md5=59c4b7d8805273b84fe4bdc52245b7c1","Earth System Physics Section, International Centre for Theoretical Physics, ICTP, PO Box 586, I-34100 Trieste, Italy","Im, E.-S., Earth System Physics Section, International Centre for Theoretical Physics, ICTP, PO Box 586, I-34100 Trieste, Italy; Coppola, E., Earth System Physics Section, International Centre for Theoretical Physics, ICTP, PO Box 586, I-34100 Trieste, Italy; Giorgi, F., Earth System Physics Section, International Centre for Theoretical Physics, ICTP, PO Box 586, I-34100 Trieste, Italy; Bi, X., Earth System Physics Section, International Centre for Theoretical Physics, ICTP, PO Box 586, I-34100 Trieste, Italy","We discuss a surrogate climate change (SCC) simulation over the Alpine region with a high resolution regional climate model (RegCM3) using a fine scale sub-grid land surface representation. Multi-year simulations are completed with an imposed illustrative 3K warming on the forcing large scale meteorological conditions and on the sea surface temperatures in the interior domain. The corresponding relative humidity is kept constant, which results in an increase of atmospheric moisture. We find that in the winter season precipitation increases consistently with the SCC approach, with a significant dependence on topographical elevation. Other components of the surface energy and water budgets also show a marked elevation dependency, mostly tied to changes in snow cover. In summer, contrary to what might be expected from the SCC forcing, precipitation decreases over the Alpine mountain chain. This is due to a local surface-atmosphere feedback mechanism involving reduced snow cover and soil moisture at the beginning of summer. Our results suggest that over the Alps during summer local feedbacks related to the surface energy and water budgets are important factors in determining the precipitation response to global warming. This result might extend to other mid-latitude mountainous areas. Copyright © 2010 by the American Geophysical Union.",,"Alpine regions; Atmospheric moisture; Climate change scenarios; Feedback mechanisms; High resolution; Land surface; Local effects; Local surfaces; Meteorological condition; Mountainous area; Regional climate models; Relative humidities; Sea surface temperatures; Snow covers; Sub-grids; Surface energies; Water budget; Winter seasons; Atmospheric humidity; Atmospheric temperature; Budget control; Feedback; Global warming; Interfacial energy; Snow; Soil moisture; Surface chemistry; Surface tension; Climate models; alpine environment; climate modeling; global warming; precipitation (climatology); regional climate; sea surface temperature; snow cover; soil moisture; water budget; Alps",,,,,,"Déqué, M., An intercomparison of regional climate simulations for Europe: Assessing uncertainties in model projections (2007) Clim. Change, 81, pp. 53-70. , doi:10.1007/s10584-006-9228-x; Dickinson, R.E., Biosphere-Atmosphere Transfer Scheme (BATS) version 1 as coupled to the NCAR Community Climate Model (1993) NCAR Tech. Note NCAR/TN-387+STR, p. 72. , Natl. Cent. for Atmos. Res., Boulder, Colo; Faggian, P., Giorgi, F., An analysis of global model projections over Italy, with particular attention to the Italian Greater Alpine Region (GAR) (2009) Clim. Change, 96, pp. 239-258. , doi:10.1007/s10584-009-9584-4; Frei, C., Heavy precipitation processes in a warmer climate (1998) Geophys. Res. Lett, 25, pp. 1431-1434. , doi:10.1029/98GL51099; Fyfe, J.C., Flato, G.M., Enhanced climate change and its detection over the Rocky Mountains (1999) J. Clim, 12, pp. 230-243. , doi:10.1175/1520-0442(1999)0120230:ECCAID2.0.